@arg repository-transition/counterstrawman-indicators
@title Emporium Indicators
@sigils [🌆/门 ✌️/女]

! conclusion: Emporium Indicators (meaningful signals for an outward-facing repository)

  + IF: The repository is treated as an outward-facing emporium that must be measured by meaningful signals.

  + HOWEVER: Raw downloads are not meaningful signals; without the right indicators the emporium cannot demonstrate its value or stay accountable to internal stakeholders.

  + THEN: Operate an explicit move on the named axis (see substructure below); steward the pattern against the declared discipline.
    + indicator: Footfall — volume and diversity of external visitors, not raw downloads.

    + indicator: Portfolio views — depth of exploration across interdisciplinary areas.

    + indicator: Exposure outside the university — citations, shares, invitations.

    + indicator: Partnership inquiries — conversions into collaborations or revenue.

    + indicator: Cross-unit usage — evidence that internal groups use each other’s assets.

    + indicator: Deposit friction — time-to-deposit, error rate, staff support load.

    + indicator: Rights clarity — number of items with clear reuse permissions.

    + indicator: Curation throughput — number of showcased items with editorial framing.

    + indicator: Inclusion signal — proportion of outputs from under-represented groups.

  + because: The repository functions as an emporium (showcase of research assets),

  + because: The emporium must be accountable to internal stakeholders,

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    + Track footfall — volume and diversity of external visitors, not raw downloads.
    + Measure portfolio views, exposure outside the university, and partnership inquiries.
    + Monitor cross-unit usage, deposit friction, rights clarity, curation throughput, and inclusion signal.
